'During the epidemic in New Orleans in , Dr . 
E. H. Barton reported that in the Fourth District the mortality was four hundred and fifty two per thousand more than double that of any other . 
In this district were three large cemeteries , in which during the previous year more than three thousand bodies had been buried . 
In other districts the proximity of cemeteries seemed to aggravate the disease . 
Mr. Cooper , in explaining the causes of some epidemics , remarks that the opening of the plague burial grounds at Eyam resulted in an immediate outbreak of disease . 
